english:
  title: Record of a Small Garden
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In a rented house at Bokjeon Ward in the capital, there lay an empty plot of ground. I tended it as a small vegetable garden—two and a half zhang in length, one-third that in width, arranged in eight or nine rows. Various greens and legumes, planted in their proper seasons, one after another, proved sufficient to supplement our stores of salt and seasoning.

    In the first year, rain and sunshine came in timely measure. Cotyledons would emerge at dawn, new leaves by dusk. The foliage glistened, the roots grew plump. Each morning's harvest left abundance for the neighbors' tables.

    In the second year, spring and summer brought drought. I carried water in jars and poured it forth—yet it was like casting drops upon a blazing fire. Seeds refused to sprout, sprouts refused to leaf, leaves refused to unfurl. Insects devoured what remained. How could I speak of roots?

    Then came the rains—torrential, relentless. By late autumn they ceased. The garden lay flooded with turbid water, buried beneath sediment and sand. The ground along the wall had collapsed and crumbled. Compared to the previous year's yield, I gathered barely half.

    In the third year, both early drought and late flooding grew severe. What I harvested was but half of that diminished half. Long ago, I learned to measure the great by the small, to discern the distant through the near. I thought: surely the realm's abundance has withered by half.

    The autumn brought no ripened grain. Winter came with empty stores. From Henan and Hebei, the people wandered forth in multitude. Bandits rose in rebellion; soldiers were sent to capture and execute them, yet could not suppress them. Spring arrived, and starving masses converged upon the capital like clouds. Within the city walls and beyond, they cried out and begged. The fallen lay without rising, their bodies heaped upon one another. The court grew anxious, officials rushed about in all directions. Every measure was taken for relief and salvation—granaries were opened, porridge was made and distributed. Yet more than half perished.

    Rice prices soared to eight or nine thousand cash per measure.

    Now, from late spring through the summer solstice, no rain has fallen. The vegetables I have planted appear as they did last year. Whether rain will come now, I do not know. I have heard that the chancellor himself has visited temples and shrines to pray for rain—surely it shall come. Yet for my small garden, it is already too late.

    There is a saying: without leaving one's threshold, one may know the world. This is no falsehood.

    Written on the seventeenth day of the fifth month, in the year Yiyou of the Zhizheng era.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhizheng era (至正) refers to the reign period of the Mongol Yuan Dynasty (1341-1368), placing this work in 1365.
  - key: ''
    value: The dramatic decline in garden yields mirrors the deteriorating conditions across the realm—a microcosm of larger historical events including famine, social unrest, and the Yuan Dynasty's eventual collapse.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gok uses his humble garden as a vehicle for philosophical reflection on fortune, providence, and the interconnection between small and large patterns in nature and society.
